Problem Definition

The problem we want to tackle is a regression problem based on the spanish_used_car_market. This dataset contains used cars offers extracted from a famous Spanish advertisement platform called Milanuncios. The data was collected by the authors using web-scraping methods. The main objective of this project is to predict the value of the cars based on the several variables - brand, model, year, etc. The result of this project will help us understand the used-cars market in Spain by predicting how much a specific car would cost or helping us choosing the right price for our car.

The table above represents a small sample of the dataset. As we can see, there are several variables which some of them are not self-explanatory. Because of that, we need to dig deeper into the dataset description to find out the meaning of these variables:

  • ad_id : A unique identifier for each sample (advertisement). Identifiers or constant variables are not useful for further analysis as they do not represent intrinsic information about the samples.
  • ad_type : Type of advertisement - Oferta (Offer) and Demanda (Demand). The authors of the dataset have only collected data of offers, so this variable is constant.
  • ad_time : Time since the creation of the advertisement in natural language.
  • ad_title : Advertisement title. It usually contains the brand and model of the car to be offered.
  • car_desc : A description in natural language of the advertisement.
  • car_km : Mileage of the car.
  • car_year : Manufacture year.
  • car_engine_type : Transmission type (Automatic or Manual).
  • car_door_num : Number of doors. As depicted in the table above, this variable is misplaced and corresponds to the _car_engine_type_ variable for most cases.
  • car_power : Car engine horsepower.
  • car_price : Selling price.
  • advertizer_type : Type of seller: Profesional (Professional) and Particular (Private).
  • image_url : URL of the advertisement thumbnail. This variable can be useful to apply Computer Vision approaches to our problem.
  • ts : It represents the exact time when the data was collected. This information, combined with _ad_time_, can give us the creation time of the advertisement.
  • region : Region within the Spanish territory where the advertisement is published.

As we can see, most of the variables will give us some insights into the problem. However, it may seem that the data is not fully usable. There are some numeric variables represented as text, the brand and model is represented as natural language, etc. Besides, there are some misplacements in the data, and the values of different columns are mixed. For those reasons, we will need to apply several transformations to the data.

  1. Drop the columns ad_id and ad_type as they are misleading or unuseful.
  2. Convert car_km and car_power variables to numerical. We need to remove any non-numerical characters from the text, and then parse the remaining content.
  3. Create years_since_manufacturing variable using ts, _ad_time_ and _car_year_. As the variable _ad_time_ is represented as natural language, we need to use an advance date parsing library. Thankfully, the dateparser library offers generic parsing of relative dates in multiple languages. This variable will represent the difference in years between the manufacturing year and the year of the advertisement. This variable will replace _car_year_.
  4. Fix variable car_door_num which is misplaced in _car_engine_type_.
  5. Extract variables brand , model and category from _ad_title_.

For the last transformation step, the advertisement title is tokenized by splitting the text into words using specific separators. Then, we assume that the first word is the brand and the rest is the model. To avoid having a very high cardinality for the model variable, it will contain two words at most, and words related to the mileage or power are filtered out. To compute the category variable, we will use another dataset. This dataset represents a database of around 10K models with its make and category. The table below shows a sample of this dataset.

One of the main challenges when dealing with multiple datasets is the task of finding entities in one source that refers to the same entity in other sources. This task is also called record linkage (Koudas et al., 2006). For our problem, we have to match brands and models from our original dataset to brands and models from the new dataset. To do so, we will utilize techniques of fuzzy string matching (Singla & Garg, 2012) - for each sample, in the original dataset, we will find the most similar entry in terms of brand and model from the other dataset. The similarity between models and brand strings are measure by Levenshtein distance. Also, to avoid connecting unrelated entities, we use a threshold of 90% of similarity.

Numerical Variables Analysis

The rest of the EDA will be carried on using the training set only to avoid introducing any bias in our modeling that may affect the generalization error.

For this dataset, only 5 out of 13 variables are numeric. The following table describes those variables briefly:

In terms of nullity, every continuous variable contains null values, so we will have to impute the missing values for those columns, or remove the variable. The car_km variable ranges between 1-16M, and it is highly likely that the upper-extreme is an outlier. For that reason, we will remove any sample with mileage over 3M kilometres. The years_since_manufacturing variable contains almost no null values, but it ranges from -1 to 114. For the purpose of this analysis, we will only consider cars dated between 1990-2020 because our main objective is to predict the price of everyday cars, not collectable or extremely outdated cars.

On the other hand, the car_door_num variable is missing for the vast majority of samples. Thus, any imputation method we would use will introduce high bias making that variable harmful for predictive modelling. So, that variable will be removed. The car_power variable ranges from 1 to 65535. Both extremes are most probably outliers, as the values are quite far from Q1 and Q3. This variable will be restricted to a range between 40 and 800 HP.

Finally, the car_price variable ranges from 0 to 16M. This case is quite similar to the previous ones, we have two extremes far away from Q1 and Q3, so we will need to clip this variable too. The new range for this variable will be 500-200K.

Once we have removed all the outliers, a good way to interpret the distribution of the variables is by plotting histograms:

As we can see, no variable follows a priori, a Gaussian distribution, but car_power is very close. As a final part of our continuous variables analysis, we will see the different correlations between the variables to discover whether there is colinearity or not. Because, as we know, if two variables have an almost perfect correlation, we can eliminate one of them and not lose much information.

plot_correlation_matrix(clean_train[clean_continuous_columns + ['car_price']],
                        figsize=(13, 7), annot_size=15)
plt.show()

The figure above shows no strong correlation between the independent variables, so we do not have to remove any features due to multicollinearity. We have also calculated Spearman's correlation coefficients. Since no variable is pure Gaussian, it makes much more sense to perform a non-parametric test based on ranking (Schober et al., 2018). We can also see how the correlation between the independent variables and the dependent variable are noticeable. It is also worth noticing how the non-parametric correlation is higher for _car_km_ and _years_since_manufacturing_. That means that we will approximate the problem better by using non-linear relationships between those variables and the labels.

In this section, we will apply some transformations to the data. The table above shows the percentage of missing values after filtering according to the previous step. Imputing the model column could introduce bias, so we will remove those samples. We will also remove the samples whose image URL is missing, and impute the missing values for the category using the most frequent value.

Subsequently, and depending on the type of data of each feature, different transformations will be applied:

  • If the data is numerical, it will be scaled so that none of the numerical variables has more weight than others. This scaling will also consider the outliers so that it will scale according to the interquartile range (first and third quartile).
  • Categorical variables like _advertizer_type_ or _car_engine_type_ will be encoded as binary.
  • Categorical variables with high cardinality like brand, model, category and region will be encoded as integers (LabelEncoder). The reason is that we will use embeddings to represent those features in a low dimensional space.

Modelling

Supervised Learning

The main objective of this project is to create a predictor of prices based on car features. For that, we have several categorical and numerical variables. One of the main challenges we face with this dataset is the high cardinality of the categorical variables. The model variable contains ~8900 different values; there are 23 different categories and 90 brands. That makes the use of One-Hot Encoding infeasible, as the number of columns generated would go up to ~9K. With such dimensionality, it is extremely difficult to fit a performant model using limited resources (Bellman, 1966). For that reason, we will train a neural network based on embedding layers (Wen et al., 2016).

Embedding layers are a powerful component that turns positive integers into dense vectors of fixed size. These layers contain trainable parameters that get updated while fitting. By using embeddings, we are able to represent categorical variables with high cardinality on a low dimensional space while keeping the semantics and relationship between values. Embedding layers were proposed originally for text data, where each word represents a different value of categorical type. In the image below, there is an example of embeddings:

<img src="/personal-blog/images/copied_from_nb/./assets/embeddings.png" alt="Example of embeddings for text data. Source: (Ruizendaal, 2020)">

The architecture we will train is depicted in the figure below. It represents a multi-input architecture where there is one embedding branch for each categorical variable and one input layer for the rest of the variables. The output from the embedding layers and the numerical input is merged into a single output and used to feed a regressor. The regressor is composed of two hidden layers with Dropout regularization and an output layer of a single unit.

The training plot shows that the learning process is unstable. However, the model is able to reduce both loss (MSE) and metric (MAE) considerably. For this project, the metric MAE is more important than the loss. The reason is that MAE is more robust to outliers, and the scale is the same as the labels, making the metric easily interpretable. For this training phase, an average error of ~1600 for the validation set is obtained.

numerical_input_columns = ['advertizer_type', 'years_since_manufacturing',
                          'car_km', 'car_power', 'car_engine_type']

model = create_keras_model(final_train, final_test, numerical_input_columns)
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.01), loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

plot_model(model, expand_nested=True)

X_train = [final_train[cols].values for cols in
           ['category', 'brand', 'model', 'region', numerical_input_columns]]

X_test = [final_test[cols].values for cols in
          ['category', 'brand', 'model', 'region', numerical_input_columns]]

y_train = final_train['car_price'].values
y_test = final_test['car_price'].values

checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("best_model.hdf5", monitor='mae', verbose=1,
                             save_best_only=True, mode='auto', period=3)

model.fit(X_train,
          y_train,
          batch_size=64,
          epochs=50,
          validation_split=0.2,
          callbacks=[PlotLearning(), checkpoint])

 Unsupervised Learning.

As a secondary objective for this project, we will apply clustering techniques to find similarities between ads, with the purpose of creating an advertisement retrieval system. The main idea is to use the features generated by the embedding layers to cluster similar ads together. To do so, we need to remove the regression part of the model and create a feature extractor. The architecture of this new model is depicted below.

test_sample = final_test['image_url'].sample(10000)
download_images(test_sample, test_images_folder)

100%|██████████| 10000/10000 [15:40<00:00, 10.63it/s]

image_features, image_ids = get_images_features(test_images_folder)

100%|██████████| 157/157 [07:07<00:00,  2.73s/it]

feature_extractor = Model(model.input, model.layers[-2].output)
features = feature_extractor.predict(X_train)
plot_model(feature_extractor, expand_nested=True)

This new architecture can be used in the same way as the original one, and it does not need retraining as the weights are copied. After applying the feature extractor the training dataset, we will apply the algorithm HDBSCAN (McInnes et al., 2017). "HDBSCAN is a clustering algorithm developed by Campello, Moulavi, and Sander. It extends DBSCAN by converting it into a hierarchical clustering algorithm, and then using a technique to extract a flat clustering based on the stability of clusters". The benefits of this type of clustering algorithms are that they do not require specifying the number of clusters. Apart from grouping instances, HDBSCAN allows us to detect outliers in the data, or to retrieve similar entities given one example.

from hdbscan import HDBSCAN

np.random.seed(1234)

cluster_data = final_train.drop(['image_url', 'car_price'], axis=1)
sample_indices = np.random.choice(features.shape[0], 10000, replace=False)

clusterer = HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=5)
cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(features[sample_indices])

samples = np.where(cluster_labels == 1)[0]
group_df = final_train.iloc[sample_indices[samples[:5]]]
clean_train.loc[group_df.index]

The table above shows a sample of a specific group. As we can see, the similarities between those instances are noticeable. All of them are advertisements from the same model, the number of years, HP and mileage are similar, and all of them are manual cars from private owners. It is worth pointing out that the car price has not been used for clustering, although the prices are quite similar. Most of the advertising platforms allow searching by brand, model, HP, etc. One way to enhance the search system is by adding this type of methods. Apart from searching by specific fields, let the user find similar cars across different brands and models.

In the supervised learning section, the image data has not been used for regression due to resources limitations. Nevertheless, images may contain important information about the problem. For the last part of this section, we will apply HDBSCAN to image features extracted from a pretrained MobileNetV2 (Howard et al., 2017). MobileNetV2 is a light CNN architecture used for classification on the ImageNet dataset. Pretrained CNN models used as feature extractors when pruning its classification or regression layers. Thankfully, Keras (Keras: The Python Deep Learning API, n.d.) offers a module to load pretrained CNN and use it as feature extractors. The image below shows a subset of a cluster.

images_clusterer = HDBSCAN(min_cluster_size=5)
images_cluster_labels = images_clusterer.fit_predict(image_features)

images_samples = np.where(images_cluster_labels == 2)[0]
images_samples = final_test.loc[image_ids[images_samples[:6]]]

group_images = [imageio.imread(url) for url in images_samples['image_url']]
render_grid(group_images, [''] * len(group_images), rows=2, figsize=(18, 8))

images_samples = np.where(images_cluster_labels == 3)[0]
images_samples = final_test.loc[image_ids[images_samples[:6]]]
group_images = [imageio.imread(url) for url in images_samples['image_url']]
render_grid(group_images, [''] * len(group_images), rows=2, figsize=(18, 8))

We can see how the algorithm has been able to group similar images. In particular, for the first set of images, it represents similar parts of the car, while the images from the second figure come from a common advertiser. Moreover, the pose and shape of those cars are similar too.

Results 

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

metric_clustering_1 = silhouette_score(features[sample_indices], cluster_labels)
metric_clustering_2 = silhouette_score(image_features, images_cluster_labels)
predictions_test = model.predict(X_test)

mae_test = mean_absolute_error(predictions_test, y_test)
r2_test = r2_score(predictions_test, y_test)

results = [
    ['Embeddings + Regressor', 'MAE', mae_test],
    ['Embeddings + Regressor', 'R2 Score', r2_test],
    ['HDBSCAN', 'Silhouette score', metric_clustering_1],
    ['HDBSCAN Images', 'Silhouette score', metric_clustering_2],
]

pd.DataFrame(results, columns=['Model', 'Metric', 'Value'])
Model Metric Value
0 Embeddings + Regressor MAE 1619.526431
1 Embeddings + Regressor R2 Score 0.915482
2 HDBSCAN Silhouette score 0.245372
3 HDBSCAN Images Silhouette score -0.166373

The results of the regression model are quite impressive. We obtained an R2 Score above 0.9, and an MAE score around 1620. Taking into account that cars are priced from 200 to 200K, an average absolute error below 2K is a fairly good result. For the clustering methods, the results are not that impressive. The silhouette score has been computed, as we do not have labels for clustering, so we can only use internal evaluation measures. For the tabular data clustering, none of the points was incorrectly assigned, but the clusters are not dense or nicely separated. For image clustering, the negative score means that some points were incorrectly assigned.

Conclusion

As a conclusion, we could say that this project has allowed us to understand the Spanish used-cars market deeply. In the EDA section, important insights were extracted from the data, which were applied in the preprocessing phase. In the modelling section, a neural network based on embedding was implemented, and it threw quite good results on both validation and test data. Apart from implementing a regressor, interesting findings have been collected from applying clustering techniques to both tabular and image data.
